-- 1. [Problem Restatement] Find the integer b with 0 ≤ b < 121 such that 24 b ≡ 1 (mod 121). 2. [Key Idea] Apply the extended Euclidean algorithm to write 1 as a Z–linear combination of 24 and 121; the coefficient of 24 (taken modulo 121) is the desired inverse. 3. [Proof] Extended Euclidean algorithm: 121 = 5·24 + 1. Hence 1 = 121 − 5·24. Rewrite modulo 121: 1 ≡ −5·24 (mod 121). Therefore 24·(−5) ≡ 1 (mod 121) ⇒ 24·116 ≡ 1 (mod 121) because −5 ≡ 116 (mod 121). (Check) 24·116 = 2784 = 23·121 + 1, confirming the congruence. 4. [Conclusion] The modular inverse of 24 modulo 121 is 116.
